The line of code:

python
Copy code
track_direction = math.atan2(next_point[1] - prev_point[1], next_point[0] - prev_point[0])
calculates the angle of the track direction between two waypoints using their coordinates. Specifically, it computes the angle (in radians) between the line connecting the two waypoints and the positive x-axis, using the atan2 function from Pythonâ€™s math module.

How math.atan2() Works:
atan2(y, x) calculates the angle between the positive x-axis and the point (x, y) in a 2D plane. It returns an angle in radians between -Ï€ and Ï€.
Itâ€™s often used to compute the direction or slope between two points in Cartesian coordinates.
Example:
Letâ€™s assume we have two waypoints on the track:

python
Copy code
