This becomes:

python
Copy code
track_direction = math.atan2(4, 4) = math.atan2(1, 1) â‰ˆ 45 degrees
This means that the direction of the track between these two points forms a 45Â° angle with the positive x-axis.

Why This is Important:
This track_direction represents the ideal heading of the car between the two waypoints. In your reward function, you compare this with the carâ€™s actual heading to see how well it is aligned with the track.

Visual Representation:
Imagine a flat 2D track.
The car is moving from (2,3) to (6,7).
The angle (45Â°) represents the direction the car should ideally be pointing as it moves forward.
If the car is not aligned with this angle (heading in a different direction), it can be penalized, since itâ€™s deviating from the trackâ€™s path.






